1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:29,277
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble,

2
00:00:29,478 --> 00:00:31,120
and fully self-awakened.

3
00:00:35,625 --> 00:00:40,850
So this evening, I thought to tackle this business of need, sufficiency and greed.

4
00:00:42,031 --> 00:00:57,088
As you know, in the UK here, well, I think it's all over the world, but in Europe and the UK, we've got these huge national debts and in the UK it's made worse by the wonderful Brexit deal that was made.

5
00:00:57,844 --> 00:01:02,890
and everybody's predicting high inflation and a downturn.

6
00:01:04,591 --> 00:01:10,918
So this is frightening, you know, because you lose your savings, you might lose your work.

7
00:01:11,537 --> 00:01:14,281
It can all be very upsetting.

8
00:01:15,522 --> 00:01:23,650
So I just thought, well, what we need to do is undermine the fear and anxiety by asking ourselves, what do we actually need?

9
00:01:24,219 --> 00:01:34,911
So what I want to do is just explain to you, and most of you won't know, what the rules for the monks are when it comes to their physical well-being.

10
00:01:36,852 --> 00:01:38,293
So the first one is shelter.

11
00:01:39,234 --> 00:01:51,206
So in the discourse on how to establish right mindfulness, the Buddha said that we should be happy with the wilderness, a root of a tree or an empty hut.

12
00:01:53,144 --> 00:01:55,626
Now, those reflect the three seasons.

13
00:01:56,328 --> 00:01:58,871
So you want a hut when it rains, in the rainy season.

14
00:01:59,471 --> 00:02:01,334
You want a tree in the hot season.

15
00:02:02,016 --> 00:02:06,501
And in the cool season, well, you can sleep anywhere and do your meditation anywhere.

16
00:02:06,902 --> 00:02:19,758
And in fact, if I remember rightly, when the Buddha settled down to his meditation, which brought about the liberation, the enlightenment, near a place called Uruvila,

17
00:02:20,161 --> 00:02:28,068
which is now, of course, Bodh Gaya, it sounds as though it was a cool season, which makes a lot of sense.

18
00:02:28,128 --> 00:02:30,931
If you're going to make a big effort, you want it to be cool.

19
00:02:35,496 --> 00:02:42,842
So when we look around our houses, our flats, or wherever we're living, you can ask yourself, well, what do you actually need?

20
00:02:43,264 --> 00:02:49,509
Not what you want, or even what is sufficient, but what do you actually need?

21
00:02:50,147 --> 00:02:55,399
So I'm thinking of things like heating.

22
00:02:55,852 --> 00:03:23,395
so there was a a little article where a man had explained that when he called up the electrical company they told him well to reduce heating just heat one room and he seemed to be quite upset by that he had a great big he sounded as i lived on his own i mean he had a family that's that's different of course but living on his own in a house he was quite upset that he had now reduces heating to one room

23
00:03:23,375 --> 00:03:41,973
well i mean if you think about what you actually need it probably is just the room you're generally living in so i met somebody at gaia house when i was teaching there i've known him for a long time and he says during winter he lives at 12 degrees centigrade

24
00:03:43,016 --> 00:03:47,963
You'd have to, if you really want to know how he does it, I can always put you in touch with him.

25
00:03:48,585 --> 00:03:52,030
But that's what he actually gets down to, 12 degrees.

26
00:03:52,050 --> 00:03:56,816
And then he says, if it's under 12, then he starts to lose it.

27
00:03:56,836 --> 00:04:00,061
He can feel the body heat really reducing too much.

28
00:04:01,282 --> 00:04:02,364
So that's all he needs.

29
00:04:02,604 --> 00:04:04,366
He needs just 12 degrees.

30
00:04:05,883 --> 00:04:11,812
But of course, we tend to walk around our houses at 25 degrees.

31
00:04:12,634 --> 00:04:17,021
In the middle of winter, you find people wearing just a t-shirt walking around the house.

32
00:04:18,064 --> 00:04:25,076
So again, if the price of gas and all this is going to go up, well, it throws it back on ourselves.

33
00:04:25,096 --> 00:04:28,161
I mean, how much do you actually need?

34
00:04:28,916 --> 00:04:39,632
There was an article for people who are really poor, who are really going to have real problems, that they can buy these rather cheap jackets and pullovers that are heated.

35
00:04:40,173 --> 00:04:53,153
You just stick the plug in and the batteries fill up and then the body armour gives you heat.

36
00:04:55,680 --> 00:05:19,596
so again it's just it's just a reflection on you know um i mean one exercise i was going to suggest at the end was what would you take with you what would you need if you were a refugee you see and of course there are people who are homeless i mean you know we know that people are living really rough uh even in the even in the depths of winter

37
00:05:19,795 --> 00:05:25,901
So it's not a case of getting to a point where we're like that, but it's a good question to ask.

38
00:05:26,302 --> 00:05:30,365
When it comes to dwelling, what do I actually need?

39
00:05:31,047 --> 00:05:35,151
I mean, I lived for quite some time just in a bedsit.

40
00:05:36,031 --> 00:05:39,115
And it was in the house of my teacher in Birmingham.

41
00:05:39,134 --> 00:05:44,199
And she had prepared this room specifically for a monk.

42
00:05:44,601 --> 00:05:50,050
It was just a bed, a place to sit next to the fire, gas fire.

43
00:05:50,810 --> 00:06:04,672
And on one side looking was just a small stove, a fridge and a little cabinet for pots and pans and stuff like that.

44
00:06:05,233 --> 00:06:06,475
I was very happy.

45
00:06:09,255 --> 00:06:29,627
so that's to do with dwelling right what do you actually need now when it comes to food uh the monastic has to go out with his bowl and uh just accept what's given so there were famines in those days and um and often they would have to just make do with whatever was put in the bowl in terms of rice um

46
00:06:32,240 --> 00:06:42,526
The Buddha, well, lay people complained to the Buddha that these monks and nuns were turning up at all times of the day and asking for food and, you know, being quite a nuisance.

47
00:06:43,369 --> 00:06:44,632
So he made a rule.

48
00:06:44,653 --> 00:06:46,737
He said, right, well, from now on,

49
00:06:46,870 --> 00:06:57,125
You have to go out in the early hours or during the morning on alms round, and you have to finish eating and everything else by noon.

50
00:06:57,766 --> 00:07:00,490
Well, there was a lot of monks who rejected that.

51
00:07:00,730 --> 00:07:01,630
They got very upset.

52
00:07:02,252 --> 00:07:05,235
They would normally have had an evening meal.

53
00:07:05,716 --> 00:07:08,540
They would normally have had three meals a day.

54
00:07:08,521 --> 00:07:10,444
And so there was a bit of a rebellion.

55
00:07:10,983 --> 00:07:17,173
And the Buddha said, look, he said, if you want to belong to this dispensation, then that's what you're going to have to do.

56
00:07:17,973 --> 00:07:21,158
And for the most part, monks try to keep that rule.

57
00:07:21,978 --> 00:07:25,624
So again, it's a case of, well, how much food do you actually need?

58
00:07:25,764 --> 00:07:33,093
And of course, there's a distinction between good food and food which is not so good for the body.

59
00:07:33,293 --> 00:07:37,528
And that's the problem, I think, with people on these food banks.

60
00:07:38,733 --> 00:07:44,112
When you get a shot of a food bank, some of it tends to be all tins, for heaven's sake.

61
00:07:47,653 --> 00:07:55,946
But again, it's just settling down and just thinking to yourself, making up a little menu for yourself, which is really basic.

62
00:07:56,266 --> 00:08:10,607
So now, when I was in India, the regular food for the ordinary worker, the ordinary person, you might say, in North India, was dal, vegetable curry, and a chapati.

63
00:08:10,987 --> 00:08:12,048
And that's what you got every day.

64
00:08:12,290 --> 00:08:15,855
You didn't say, well, I'm going to have a Chinese today.

65
00:08:16,122 --> 00:08:21,771
It was just, you know, dal, vegetable curry, and a chapati.

66
00:08:22,112 --> 00:08:23,613
And that's what you may do with.

67
00:08:25,175 --> 00:08:37,576
Interestingly enough, when they started to recruit men during conscription for the Second World War, they were really taken aback to find that many of the men weren't having three meals a day at all.

68
00:08:37,897 --> 00:08:43,125
They were actually eating really bad and were happy to join the army just to get some decent food, I think.

69
00:08:46,226 --> 00:08:59,634
So it's like another little exercise you might set yourself for a little while anyway, is to have a day as if you were poor, as if you couldn't just buy the food you need.

70
00:08:59,715 --> 00:09:00,416
What would you eat?

71
00:09:00,616 --> 00:09:04,083
What would sustain you for that day?

72
00:09:04,942 --> 00:09:15,854
So again, it's just taking away this fear that if we become very poor for one reason or another, that's not the end of the world.

73
00:09:15,953 --> 00:09:16,815
You just make do.

74
00:09:23,081 --> 00:09:26,725
I mean, I'm old enough to have memories of just after the war.

75
00:09:26,945 --> 00:09:32,451
And I remember going to my aunt's for food.

76
00:09:32,683 --> 00:09:56,768
uh on the toast you see you put the butter on the toast and then you scraped it off and what you were left with was just a sort of a little suggestion and then they did the same with the jam i mean i couldn't believe it i was only a kid i must have been about six or seven you know just looking at this you put a jam on on the bread and then scraped it all off and then stuck it on another piece

77
00:09:58,047 --> 00:09:59,937
So all these were considered luxury.

78
00:10:00,158 --> 00:10:03,214
I mean, the food was the bread itself.

79
00:10:06,518 --> 00:10:18,351
When it comes to clothing, again, the Buddha noticed that people were coming away with huge amounts of cloth from the lay people.

80
00:10:18,972 --> 00:10:27,982
And so he actually set out one night on a cold night, this would have been the cold season, to actually decide how many robes you actually need.

81
00:10:28,663 --> 00:10:35,731
So in the beginning of the night, he had his lower robe and the top robe, this one here.

82
00:10:35,711 --> 00:11:03,693
and then as the night got colder he needed another robe so he took another road and then towards the end of the night you know the coldest hour is just before dawn he felt he needed one more so he he put the last two together right and those are your three robes the lower robe the upper robe and the sangati the one that that you see monks putting over their shoulder and that was it and that was the rule then that's all you could have um

83
00:11:03,673 --> 00:11:06,495
But of course, rules are rules and

84
00:11:07,352 --> 00:11:11,256
And you get ways around it by having extra cloth, which is a bit cheeky, I know.

85
00:11:11,878 --> 00:11:16,482
But it was just coming down to what do you actually need?

86
00:11:16,863 --> 00:11:20,767
And I mean, of course, we're talking about the tropics, but what do you actually need?

87
00:11:20,927 --> 00:11:22,109
How many coats do you need?

88
00:11:22,188 --> 00:11:23,811
How many pair of shoes do you need?

89
00:11:24,530 --> 00:11:35,503
And it's just drawing ourselves down to that basic need that I think gets rid of a lot of the fear that comes from a loss of...

90
00:11:35,482 --> 00:11:54,032
a loss of wealth whatever that wealth is a loss of your job and so on and so forth and just as an aside of course it does make us more aware of where we're getting our clothes from you know

91
00:11:54,721 --> 00:12:06,216
uh i met somebody and they they showed me this uh i was i was in shropshire and they showed me this jumper they just bought you see and they they said they bought it for so many pounds i think

92
00:12:06,414 --> 00:12:08,298
or three or four pounds or something.

93
00:12:08,957 --> 00:12:15,086
And they'd gone to this other shop, probably Marks and Spencer's, and it was a similar jumper, it was 12 pounds, you see.

94
00:12:15,506 --> 00:12:23,138
And when I said to them, yeah, but this is probably made in one of those satanic sweatshops in Bangladesh, it was taken by surprise.

95
00:12:23,378 --> 00:12:25,942
It hadn't even occurred to him to think that way.

96
00:12:29,547 --> 00:12:35,595
Now the final one, so we've done shelter, food,

97
00:12:36,756 --> 00:13:04,975
clothing the final one is medicine now the buddha said that we should be contented with fermented cow's urine now that might come as a big surprise but in fact it's a it's a very well-known ayurvedic medicine it's an antibiotic let me just get it here it's a it's an antibiotic

98
00:13:05,562 --> 00:13:31,249
anti-fungal and if you take it regularly it maintains the homeostasis of the body to lower cholesterol relieve tension enhance liver function and slow down aging so tomorrow morning you need to get out there and get your bottle of fermented cow's urine

99
00:13:32,966 --> 00:13:35,788
So that's what we're supposed to be happy with.

100
00:13:36,110 --> 00:13:37,671
Now, frankly, I've never tried it.

101
00:13:38,532 --> 00:13:47,359
So I don't want to say whether it's any good or not, but it's definitely Ayurvedic medicine and people do drink it.

102
00:13:50,182 --> 00:13:59,909
So here we have this whole business of really asking ourselves what we need, what we actually need to sustain life.

103
00:13:59,929 --> 00:14:02,231
So this is only the physical needs, yeah?

104
00:14:02,330 --> 00:14:08,597
I mean, there's also the other side, our cultural needs, our heart needs and things like that.

105
00:14:09,538 --> 00:14:24,517
In the Buddha's instructions to the monks, basically, the day was to be spent meditating and remembering and studying and understanding the Dharma.

106
00:14:24,537 --> 00:14:28,903
So in those days, of course, you had to memorize the teaching, yeah?

107
00:14:29,523 --> 00:14:31,745
You know, they didn't have...

108
00:14:34,020 --> 00:14:37,225
clever little gadgets like we've got to remember things.

109
00:14:39,368 --> 00:14:47,998
So one exercise, you know, you can just set yourself is to live one day, one day with just what you need and just find out for yourself.

110
00:14:53,345 --> 00:14:59,211
The second one is more to do with just, you know, lifting the level of it to sufficiency.

111
00:14:59,711 --> 00:15:01,934
And that depends upon, I think, a lot on

112
00:15:02,523 --> 00:15:20,952
on our culture for instance when it comes to clothes you know people need a set of clothes for work they need a set of clothes for leisure set of clothes for climbing mountains and things like that so it's not a case of uh you know making ourselves miserable

113
00:15:21,153 --> 00:15:27,581
But just being clear in ourselves as to what we actually need.

114
00:15:28,081 --> 00:15:50,350
And I think that if you spend just one day with need, then I think that undermines a lot of the fear and anxiety that comes about with the loss of wealth, no matter how much or how little wealth you had, to suddenly find yourself unemployed and on the dole, which is pretty miserable.

115
00:15:50,330 --> 00:15:55,240
You just find you can live with it, at least at a physical level.

116
00:15:58,485 --> 00:16:00,549
And then, of course, there's a final one of greed.

117
00:16:00,570 --> 00:16:05,219
Well, that takes us to another step that does.

118
00:16:05,239 --> 00:16:07,923
So I think most of us know when we're being greedy.

119
00:16:09,888 --> 00:16:11,510
I think I need to go into that too much.

120
00:16:12,452 --> 00:16:35,996
so um a couple of exercises there when it comes to food you know just to have one day with what you feel is the is the cheapest and most sustainable uh food that you could have that was good for the body uh just one day a week you know just to remind ourselves yeah

121
00:16:36,989 --> 00:16:42,956
And when it comes to clothes, just go through the wardrobe and just see how much of clothes you're not wearing.

122
00:16:43,657 --> 00:16:58,354
I remember somebody was in the habit of, in their wardrobe, if they used a piece from it, a shirt or some sort of dress, they would put it at one end.

123
00:16:59,134 --> 00:17:05,342
And then over the year, they would see all the clothes they hadn't actually used and they would take them down to the charity shop.

124
00:17:07,499 --> 00:17:14,527
So there's all sorts of little tricks that we can play on ourselves in order to actually just come down to sufficiency.

125
00:17:15,008 --> 00:17:16,630
And eventually it saves a lot of money.

126
00:17:16,910 --> 00:17:22,176
When it comes to heating, that's really quite crucial for us these days.

127
00:17:22,998 --> 00:17:25,119
Our heating bill is going to go up something awful.

128
00:17:26,040 --> 00:17:36,814
But just by being careful with it and wearing jumpers, it won't be that heavy on us, I don't think.

129
00:17:38,920 --> 00:17:39,500
Very good.

130
00:17:40,502 --> 00:18:00,996
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and they have not caused any confusion and that by your devotion to practice and the practice of poverty, simplicity, that's the word simplicity, you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

